{"cursor":"1773","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\nThe 'Abolition of Poindings and Warrant Sales Act 2001' was an act by the\nScottish Parliament which abolished the previous practice in which a debtorâs\ngoods are priced (poinding) in preparation for the enforced sale of the debtorâs\npossessions (warrant sale) by amending the Debtors (Scotland) Act 1987. The\noriginal Bill was introduced in 1999 as a member's bill by Tommy Sheridan MSP, [http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/vli/education/resources/learningResource-\ns/pdfs/CaseStudyMembersBills.pdf Case Study â Members Bills]\nscottish.parliament.uk, accessed 2 August 2009 at the time the sole member\nof the Scottish Socialist Party in the Parliament. Prior to being elected in\n1999, Tommy Sheridan had been a leading figure in the anti-poll tax campaign\nduring which poindings were commonplace where protesters who refused to pay the\ntax had their household possessions valued and sold by local councils seeking to\nrecover outstanding debts.\n\nThough the original draft of the bill proposed that it would have immediate\neffect, this was subsequently amended so as to delay the introduction of the Act\nby over a year by which time it was repealed by the Debt Arrangement and\nAttachment (Scotland) Act 2002, asp 17.\n","linknr":164,"url":"Abolition_of_Poindings_and_Warrant_Sales_Act_2001","recorded":1375055877,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Abolition_of_Poindings_and_Warrant_Sales_Act_2001&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Abolition_of_Poindings_and_Warrant_Sales_Act_2001&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%